Champions Full Day Programs are located inside of Stottlemyer Early Childhood, all WWCSD Elementary Schools and Stevenson Middle School (Adams and Franklin students welcome here)!
Open at 6:45am - 6:30pm; open non-school days too; closed holidays!
We will help facilitate an environment for student learning during school hours; all meals served!

DHHS Families (MiBridges) – If you receive state assistance you may qualify for FREE child care. Please call or email today for more information!

Hegira Health provides access to a safe and private network of behavioral health resources, and therapy supports by trained counselors for children and families ages 14 years and older.

These sessions are with professional counselors to provide screenings, brief interventions and treatment. This service is available for youth and adults who are approaching a crisis related to or triggered by the COVID-19 pandemic. Call or text for help 24/7 at 855-966-3313.

Wayne-Westland Family Resource Center
May 26 at 3:37 PM ·

Do you have a student who attends Wayne-Westland Community Schools, and need assistance with basic needs? Could you use community resource numbers for food or utility assistance? Are you struggling to afford basic need items such as hygiene products? Do you need numbers to programs offering telehealth services for medical and mental health needs? Please contact our Family Resource Center- we may be able to help! Please email us: FRC@wwcsd.net or message us on Facebook! You can also call us at: 734-419-2709, and leave a message for us to contact you. We are here to help!

post_text:
Bond Construction Groundbreaking Ceremony at William D. Ford Career-Technical Center

Monday, May 11, 2020, was the groundbreaking ceremony on the District’s first Bond construction project. The William D. Ford Career-Technical Center will be under construction through fall 2020. There will be a new front entrance that includes a main office addition with secure entry. An expansion to the Culinary Arts area includes a total kitchen remodel and banquet center. In addition, there will be updates throughout the entire building.

Voters in Wayne-Westland passed a $158 million bond in November 2018 to implement improvements at each of the District's schools. The improvements will address safety, security, health, energy efficiency, accessibility, and technology issues.

This week, four WWCSD elementary EMU Bright Futures sites (Hicks Elementary, Elliott Elementary, Hamilton Elementary, and Schweitzer Elementary) partnered with local business owner Lou Toarmina and Crystal Murphy, to bring a curbside take away Family Pizza night to EMUBF families. Participating families received a pizza night kit that included conversation starters and pizza fraction math kit.. The math kit included a fraction memory game, story problems, fraction vocabulary, using art to practice fraction comprehension and more!

EMUBF staff and participating families send their deepest gratitude to Toarmina’s Pizza on S. Wayne Rd. in Westland (Lou, Crystal, and staff) for partnering with us. Their organization, hard work, and welcoming presence made this a wonderful experience for all involved. We are excited to continue to partner with Toarmina’s in the future.

Thank you EMU Bright Futures!

FREE LUNCHES!

HIGH VELOCITY SPORTS
46245 Michigan Ave. in Canton

Free lunches for anyone in need from 11:00am-1:00pm, Monday-Friday on a week to week basis. Cars can pull up to the front door and a sack lunch or lunches will be delivered to the vehicle. Each lunch will consist of a peanut butter and jelly (or jelly only) sandwich, a bag of chips, a piece of fruit, and a juice box.
The lunch program is an effort to help support the very communities that have supported HVS for the past 20 years and is NOT limited to Canton residents. Instead, it is open, like all of our programming to everyone.

post_text:
Statement from Interim Superintendent Jill Simmons

We have been made aware that some posts have been made on social media in regards to when our schools will re-open to students. At no time did any of our staff say that Wayne-Westland Community Schools will remain closed until a vaccine is developed for COVID-19. Our schools are closed for face-to-face instruction for the remainder of the 2019-20 school year as a result of an executive order by Governor Whitmer. We will take direction from our State and federal officials, the Michigan Department of Health and Human Services and the CDC on the safest way and time to return to in-person instruction at our schools.

post_text:
Making Family Mealtimes Fun
Sitting down together for a meal whenever you can is a great way to connect with your family. Keeping it relaxed is key to making sure you are getting the most out of this time together, including talking, laughing and choosing healthy foods. Talk to each other. Conversation starters include:
1. Give each family member the spotlight to share their highlight, lowlight, and “funnylight” from the day or week.
2. If our family lived in a zoo, what animals would we be and why?
3. If you could have one super power, what would it be and why?
4. If you were stranded on a desert island and could only have one food to eat, what would it be and why?

City of Westland - Administration
April 11 at 10:35 AM ·

The Jefferson Barns Learning Lab (JBLL) continues to serve our community even though their tutoring services are currently closed.
The JBLL uses 3D printers in the Learning Lab, and with a shortage of personal protective equipment in hospitals, many schools have been printing headbands for face shields. Using the three printers from the JBLL lab, along with another printer from Wayne-Westland Community Schools, they are printing on average, one headband per hour for protective face shields. They have partnered with the Protect MI group, which has provided the 3D files for printing, as well as supply chain logistics. They are using a design that has been approved by several local hospitals to use our 3D printed headbands along with a clear plastic shield and a piece of elastic.
As much as they can, the JBLL strives to help our community any way they can. Stay home and stay safe! #DoingMiPart #CompassionateCity

shared_text:
Kelly Dunn
April 1 at 8:27 AM ·

The staff at Edison received an email from our Social Worker that one of our families was having a hard time getting food and every day things because of Covid-19. Within 24 hours the staff came together and dropped all of this at the curb at the school for mom to pick up and I took this picture before 5 more bags showed up. There may be a lot of bashing on schools and how they are handling this shut down right now, but this right here is more important than anything. This is how Wayne-Westland Community Schools handles a crisis. We come together and take care of our own. I am so proud to be an employee of Edison today. 💙 #edisoneaglessoar #wwcstrong

Food Distribution Day a Success!

Today Wayne-Westland Community Schools staff held our first curb-side food distribution for our families and 2,200 students received three breakfasts and three lunches.

Thank you to all who helped and to all who came through the line with a friendly smile and a wave for us.

We will be back at John Glenn High School from 10 am- 1 pm on Monday, March 23, 2020, to pass out food to families with children up to 18 years old or adults 18-26 years old in our adult transitional programs. We hope to see your smiling face!

shared_text:
City of Westland - Administration
March 11 at 3:26 PM ·

Westland: Are you ready to be counted? Census 2020 is around the corner.
Mayor Wild urges Westland Residents to be counted in 2020 Census
This year the U.S. Census Bureau will begin its, once in a decade, count of every individual in the United States - no small feat. The Census is much more than just a head count. It provides a picture of our nation that helps determine how and where federal resources and money is used. It also helps us see how our communities have changed over time. That’s why an accurate count is so important, and that means we need everyone in our state and the City of Westland to be a part of it.
This is our one chance in 10 years to make sure Westland gets everything we're due. #Westlandcounts
